result.execSummary:
The defendant Jaclyn Giikwe Taylor was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Jail credit was provided by Attorney Harrington after the Plea/Sentencing Hearing concluded.

miscConds.notes:
1) The defendant shall pay at a minimum rate of $25 per month to Probation.  The first payment is due by the end of December, 2022.
2) If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. 
3) The defendant must provide DNA and pay the surcharge; the analysis may be expunged upon application to the Department of Justice.

1) The defendant shall obtain a GED.
2) The defendant shall maintain gainful employment or be enrolled in school.

1) The defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety; no use or possession of any alcohol, illegal drugs, paraphernalia, or controlled substances without a valid prescription. 
2) Defendant is restricted from any establishments whose primary purpose is the sale of alcohol- such as bars, taverns, beer tents, and liquor stores.

1) The defendant shall continue with her mental health regimen and take all medications as they are prescribed to her.
2) The DOC has the discretion to impose a curfew.

Burnett County case 22CF28 was DRI.
